03978nam a22006975i 9780823238392DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20102010nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232383927 a10.1515/97808232383922doi  a(DE-B1597)555060  a(OCoLC)680628937  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aB66 .V36 2010 7aLIT0041302bisacsh04a1901 aVardoulakis, Dimitris, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Doppelganger :bLiterature's Philosophy /cDimitris Vardoulakis. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2010] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (336 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tPreamble, or An Other Opening -- tIntroduction, or The Reflections of the Doppelgänger -- tChapter One. The Critique of Loneliness -- tChapter Two. The Subject of Modernity -- tChapter Three. The Task of the Doppelgänger -- tChapter Four. The Politics of the Doppelgänger -- tChapter Five. Self-Inscriptions -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Doppelgänger or Double presents literature as the "double" of philosophy. There are historical reasons for this. The genesis of the Doppelgänger is literature's response to the philosophical focus on subjectivity. The Doppelgänger was coined by the German author Jean Paul in 1796 as a critique of Idealism's assertion of subjective autonomy, individuality and human agency. This critique prefigures post-War extrapolations of the subject as decentred. From this perspective, the Doppelgänger has a "family resemblance" to current conceptualizations of subjectivity. It becomes the emblematic subject of modernity. This is the first significant study on the Doppelgänger's influence on philosophical thought. The Doppelgänger emerges as a hidden and unexplored element both in conceptions of subjectivity and in philosophy's relation to literature. Vardoulakis demonstrates this by employing the Doppelgänger to read literature philosophically and to read philosophy as literature. The Doppelgänger then appears instrumental in the self-conception of both literature and philosophy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aLiteraturexPhilosophy. 0aPhilosophy. 0aSubject (Philosophy). 4aLiterary Studies. 4aPhilosophy & Theory. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311070729840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823238392zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823238392423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823238392/original  a978-3-11-070729-8  Fordham University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK